Why isn't the Fed doing its job?
STANFORD – The nomination of new board members for the US central bank, the Federal Reserve, gives Americans – and the US Congress – the opportunity to reflect on the world's most important central bank and its future course.
The obvious first question is how it was possible for the Fed to so severely fail to fulfill its most important mandate – price stability.
That the Fed was completely taken by surprise by the current inflation suggests a fundamental failure.
Now institutional confidence assessment is undoubtedly called for.
However, while monetary policy makes headlines, the Fed is now primarily significant as a financial regulator.
A further major question is whether it will use its enormous power to advance climate or social policy.
The Fed could, for example, refuse credit to companies in the fossil fuel sector, demand that banks extend loans only to firms with certified net-zero emissions plans, or steer credit allocation towards desired alternatives.
Furthermore, it could decide to explicitly incorporate regulation for equality or ethnic justice by instructing banks on where and to whom to extend credits, who to hire and who to fire, and so forth.
However, before we address the question of which direction the Fed's regulation will move or should move in, it is first necessary to clarify the Fed's grave failure.
In 2008, the US government made a consequential decision: Financial institutions could still primarily finance risky investments through the sale of short-term, run-sensitive debt instruments, but armies of new regulatory agencies would henceforth assess the risk sensitivity of the institution's assets.
The hope was that regulatory bodies would no longer overlook large chunks like subprime mortgages on bank balance sheets.
However, over the following ten years of detailed regulation and regular scenario-based stress tests, the Fed's regulatory army never once questioned what would actually happen in the case of a pandemic.
When the pandemic then actually hit in early 2020, the Fed abandoned its "never again" promises from 2008 and intervened on an even larger scale.
In March, the commercial banks proved unable to act as intermediaries in the market for ordinary US Treasury securities.
Therefore, the Fed supported the market.
Critics had long pointed out the problems with the Federal Reserve's liquidity rules. The corrections on the markets would have been simple, but obvious reforms had been pushed to the back burner.
Later there was a run on money market funds.
The Fed rescued the money market funds again.
Nothing is easier to address than runs on the money market, but they never happened.
Additionally, the Fed also financed the issuance of new municipal bonds and supported corporate bond prices by essentially providing a guarantee on the lines of "whatever it takes."
In 2008, the Fed and the US Department of the Treasury had resisted the idea of raising the market price of all mortgages as part of the financial industry bailout package - the Troubled Asset Relief Program.
However, in 2020, a clear floor for corporate bond prices, among other things, was established with the "Powell put."
The predictable rebuttal to this criticism will be: So what?
The lockdowns due to Covid-19 could have triggered a financial crisis.
The flood of rescue measures has worked so well that our problem today is inflation.
We do not need to worry about systemic risks, as the Fed and the US Department of the Treasury will simply extinguish any new fire with another flood of money.
The problem lies, however, in the incentives these strategies have created.
Why bother with emergency measures or balance sheet buffers for purchases at falling prices, providing liquidity, or treating a "fire sale" as a buying opportunity?
The Fed will overshadow everyone and scoop up all the profits.
Why issue stocks as a company when one can simply take out a loan, knowing that the state supports the debt or helps the company out of trouble, as was the case with airlines?
Why hesitate as an investor when buying dubious papers, if their value is guaranteed by yet another "whatever-it-takes" promise from the Fed during bad times?
No wonder America is sinking into debt.
It is assumed that taxpayers will bear the losses in the next downturn.
Student loans, state pensions, and mortgages pile up, waiting for their turn in Uncle Sam's rescue operation.
However, every new crisis requires even more extensive transfusions.
Bondholders will eventually refuse to pour more money into rescue operations, and people will not rejoice with trillions of newly printed money.
If the rescue packages, which are expected by all, do not materialize, we will wake up in a大火灾，并且消防队已经被摧毁。
In 2008, regulators and lawmakers at least recognized the moral risk and feared that investors would profit in good times while taxpayers would bear the losses in bad times.
In 2020, there was debate over whether rescue actions were now nothing but self-congratulation.
Exactly the Fed, which in 2008 failed to see the risks of subprime mortgages just as it failed to anticipate the pandemic in 2020 and now wants to conduct stress tests in light of “climate risks,” will certainly also overlook the next war, the next pandemic, the next state bankruptcy, or some other disruptive event.
The regulators of the Fed do not even ask about the mentioned events.
And while acronyms are produced for "networks," "strategic interactions," "network effects," and "credit cycles," it has not been possible to define the "systemic" risk beyond it becoming a catchall term that grants regulatory authorities comprehensive power.
Regulatory agencies will never be able to predict risks, accurately measure the value of financial institutions' assets, or ensure that enormous debts are always paid.
We need to reverse the fundamental premise of a financial system where the state always stands ready to bail out mountains of debt in bad times. And we need to do this before the fire department is tested.
Better regulation can bridge partisan divides.
The Left is right in saying that the large banks are inefficient oligopolies that benefit most Americans very little.
However, it assumes the wrong cause.
A massive effort to comply with regulations presents a significant obstacle to market entry.
The call for "more" regulation is pointless.
Regulatory provisions are either smart or dumb, effective or ineffective, riddled with unwanted consequences or well-designed.
We need better regulation.
We need more capital, not thousands of pages of regulations.
Capital provides a buffer against all shocks and requires regulatory agencies to possess no prophetic abilities.
The Fed has scandalously stopped companies in the Narrow Banking and payment services sector, which could contribute to meeting the financial needs of many people in America.
Before it commits to saving the planet and making amends for injustices, the Fed should be held accountable for how inadequately it fulfills its fundamental task of protecting the financial system.
